Duck typing is a programming concept that is used to determine the type of an object based on its properties and methods, rather than its actual type. In other words, if an object has the same properties and methods as another object, it is considered to be of the same type, even if it is not explicitly declared as such. This is known as the "duck test": if it looks like a duck, swims like a duck, and quacks like a duck, then it probably is a duck.

TypeScript supports duck typing through the use of structural type system. When TypeScript compares two types, it checks whether they have the same structure, i.e. whether they have the same properties and methods with the same types. If they do, then TypeScript considers them to be compatible. This allows for a more flexible and dynamic way of working with types than traditional static type systems.

For example, consider the following code:
```
interface Duck {
  walk: () => void;
  quack: () => void;
}

function doSomething(duck: Duck) {
  duck.walk();
  duck.quack();
}

const myObject = {
  walk: () => console.log('Walking...'),
  quack: () => console.log('Quacking...')
};

doSomething(myObject); // This is fine, myObject has the same structure as Duck
```
Although `myObject` is not explicitly declared to be of type `Duck`, TypeScript is able to infer that it is compatible with the `Duck` interface because it has the same properties and methods with the same types. Thus, the call to `doSomething(myObject)` is valid and will not result in any type errors.

