To convert Markdown to HTML in C++, you can use a library like cmark-gfm (GitHub flavored Markdown). Here's an example of how to create a function that takes a reference to a std::string containing Markdown formatted text and returns a std::string containing HTML formatted text using the cmark-gfm library.

First, download and install the cmark-gfm library: https://github.com/github/cmark-gfm

Then, include the necessary headers and write the function:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <cmark-gfm.h>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string &markdown) {
    cmark_gfm_parser *parser = cmark_gfm_parser_new(CMARK_GFM_DEFAULT);
    cmark_node *document = cmark_gfm_parse_document(parser, markdown.c_str(), markdown.size(), NULL);
    cmark_gfm_renderer *renderer = cmark_gfm_html_renderer_new(CMARK_GFM_HTML_RENDERER_OPTIONS_DEFAULT);

    std::string html;
    html.resize(cmark_gfm_render_html(renderer, document, NULL));
    cmark_gfm_render_html(renderer, document, &html[0]);

    cmark_node_free(document);
    cmark_gfm_html_renderer_free(renderer);
    cmark_gfm_parser_free(parser);

    return html;
}
```

This function creates a new parser, parses the input Markdown string, creates an HTML renderer, and then renders the parsed document into an HTML formatted string. The function finally returns the resulting HTML string.

Don't forget to link your project with the cmark-gfm library. If you're using CMake, add the following lines to your `CMakeLists.txt`:

```cmake
find_package(cmark-gfm REQUIRED)
target_link_libraries(your_target_name cmark-gfm)
```

Replace `your_target_name` with the name of your target (e.g., executable or library).

